Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Two weeks ago in Kyiv, I sat down one-on-one with President Zelenskyy to advance a clear and unified vision: end this brutal war, secure a full and unconditional ceasefire, guarantee Ukraine‚Äôs long-term security, and rebuild a free and sovereign nation that can never again be threatened by tyranny.

At the heart of our discussion was the urgent need to align Ukraine‚Äôs economic recovery with global security‚Äîand that meant locking in a strategic minerals partnership to power both.

Today‚Äôs historic U.S.-Ukraine minerals agreement reflects those conversations and the strategic vision we laid out together. By advancing this partnership, we are not only fueling Ukraine‚Äôs long-term recovery‚Äîwe are denying Putin control over the critical resources that power modern technology and global security.

This is how we confront aggression: with unity, with purpose, and with the full weight of American leadership. Those who bankrolled Putin‚Äôs war machine will not profit from Ukraine‚Äôs peace. That future belongs to the Ukrainian people‚Äîand we will stand with them every step of the way.

Peace through strength.

Today, with broad bipartisan support, the House passed three Congressional Review Act resolutions to put a stop to Gavin Newsom and California's extreme vehicle emissions mandates. California's extreme emissions mandates would have made cars and trucks more expensive and less available for everyone, not just in our state but nationwide.

Consumers would see massive increases in costs if they chose a non-electric vehicle, and availability of some models has already been severely restricted in California. By passing these resolutions, the House made it clear that we won't let one states radical agenda dictate what Americans can drive. People deserve the freedom to choose the vehicles that work best for them‚Äînot to be forced into unaffordable electric vehicles that may not work for them. I was pleased to see the House stand up for commonsense to protect hardworking families from even higher costs.

Happy Asian American, Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander Heritage Month! This month, we recognize the contributions AANHPI communities have made to the history, culture and strength of our nation.

As Whip of the Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus, I am proud to stand with AANHPI communities in Sacramento County and across the country. At a time when too many seek to divide us or erase the stories of our diverse communities, it is more important than ever to lift up the voices, histories and achievements of Asian Americans, Native Hawaiians and Pacific Islanders.

I remain committed to ensuring every American ‚Äî no matter where they come from or what they look like ‚Äî has the opportunity to achieve the American Dream. Together, we will continue working toward a future rooted in opportunity, respect and freedom for all.

The New York State Assembly‚Äôs decision to pass this disgusting assisted suicide bill is a shameful attack on the sanctity of life and a betrayal of our most vulnerable citizens. This radical legislation, driven by Governor Hochul‚Äôs Far Left allies, normalizes the termination of human life under the guise of ‚Äòcompassion,‚Äô putting the elderly, disabled, and terminally ill at risk of coercion and despair. As a proud pro-life advocate, I am appalled that Albany Democrats would prioritize this culture of death over protecting the dignity and worth of every New Yorker.

Instead of investing in palliative care, mental health support, and life-affirming resources for those facing terminal illness, this legislation offers an immoral shortcut that devalues human life. It sends a chilling message to our seniors and disabled communities that their lives are expendable.

New Yorkers deserve better than Far Left policies that erode our moral foundation and push families toward heartbreak. I call on the State Senate to reject this dangerous bill and stand up for the voiceless. As the representative of New York‚Äôs 21st District, I will continue to champion life at every stage and fight against the extremist agenda of Hochul and her Albany Democrats. We must restore New York‚Äôs commitment to the protection of all its citizens.

Name: LaMalfa, Doug
text:
Today the House passed my resolution to stop the Biden Administration‚Äôs politically motivated attempt to list the longfin smelt as endangered in the San Francisco Bay-Delta.

This listing isn‚Äôt about science‚Äîit‚Äôs about control. The Administration and activist judges have weaponized the Endangered Species Act to block progress on California water policy. Even Stanford‚Äôs water policy experts questioned the science behind this listing. It‚Äôs based on cherry-picked data, surveys that weren‚Äôt even designed to track longfin smelt, and a process that ignored peer review and key information gaps.

What does it mean in practice? Another layer of conflicting regulations that dump tens of millions of acre-feet of water out to the Pacific Ocean, while California farmers are left with a fraction of what they were promised.

Congress isn‚Äôt going to sit back while bureaucrats and lawsuits keep choking off the water system that feeds our farms and our economy. I‚Äôm proud to see the House take a stand.

Name: Keating, William R.
text:
A strong U.S.-Ukraine relationship is critical to ensuring a long-lasting and durable peace in Ukraine. This long-awaited critical minerals deal is an important aspect of our bilateral relationship and an example of how, if we work together, we can support Ukraine‚Äôs sovereignty and keep the transatlantic alliance safe from future Russian aggression.
 
While this agreement is constructive and a good example of working with Ukraine, it does not supplant our commitment to supporting Ukraine‚Äôs sovereignty and territorial integrity, a commitment which goes back to the 1994 Budapest Memorandum and the more recently established Ukraine Defense Contact Group with an alliance of more than 50 countries.
 
Unfortunately, the Trump-led negotiations to end the war have appeased the Kremlin, isolated Ukraine, and brought tension to our transatlantic relationship. This is no way to treat our allies and our friends, let alone the Kremlin. Nor is it a practical solution for finding a lasting ceasefire and peace deal which must include credible security guarantees.
 
The Trump administration must move forward with a clear sense of vision and purpose to end this conflict and with the acknowledgement that Vladimir Putin is the aggressor and the impediment to peace. Any alternative will leave the Kremlin stronger and both Ukraine and the transatlantic alliance in a weaker position than before.

text:
It was deeply moving today to welcome Abigail Mor Edan to the Capitol for Members of Congress to meet this incredibly brave young girl. 
¬†
On October 7th, 2023, Hamas terrorists forced their way into Abigail‚Äôs family home in Israel. Her parents, Roy and Smadar, were shot and killed while attempting to shield the then 3-year-old Abigail from Hamas, while her older siblings Michael and Amalia hid silently in a closet for 14 hours before being rescued. Abigail was taken hostage by the terrorists, who held her in captivity for 51 days. Abigail‚Äôs 4th birthday occurred as she was still being held hostage.
¬†
I learned of Abigail‚Äôs story from her aunt, Liz Hirsh Naftali, soon after the October 7th attacks. Liz gave me Abigail‚Äôs picture and asked me to share her story. On a Senate delegation trip to Israel, I held up that picture during an international news conference to show the world that Hamas had taken innocent hostages, like this 3-year-old girl who had just witnessed the murder of both her parents. Abigail‚Äôs photo accompanied me at events throughout her captivity as a reminder of the families torn apart by the attacks and the urgent need to bring all the hostages home.
¬†
Today‚Äôs event was an occasion to celebrate the unbelievable strength and resilience of this now 5-year-old girl whose life has already been marked by unimaginable tragedy, and yet who continues to inspire with her ceaseless courage and spirit.
¬†
It was also a solemn reminder of the hostages that still remain in captivity today, and the work that must continue to bring those remaining hostages home to their families.

Name: Higgins, Clay
text:
America is 37 thousand billion dollars in debt. Liberals scream ‚Äútax the rich‚Äù, but we don‚Äôt have a revenue problem, we have a spending problem. If we seized 100% of all the wealth of every American billionaire, all 902 of them, not just 100% of their income, I‚Äôm talking about 100% of their entire net wealth which is $6.8 trillion‚Ä¶ it would fund America for roughly 1 year. That‚Äôs it. Then what? Point is, the whole liberal concept of ‚Äúseize the money from the billionaires to pay for endless crap for the federal government‚Äù is not only unconstitutional and contrary to our deepest core principles‚Ä¶ it‚Äôs also very, very stupid. Do the math. We‚Äôre just spending waaaay too much money, and our Republic is careening towards bankruptcy. If we don‚Äôt make a significant correction right now, while we have enough conservatives in power to force the necessary reforms through Congress, and a President who is courageous enough to lead us towards a balanced budget, then We the People will lose our country to complete financial collapse, on the heads of our children. 
 The federal government was not ‚Äútoo small‚Äù in 2019. Think about that. Correction of spending back to pre-COVID levels is reasonable. If it was up to me, I‚Äôd take this thing back to 1975 levels, but we can save the country by just backing up from the INSANE levels of deficit spending pushed through Congress since the CCP lab-grown plandemic. 
  Stand with us America. We‚Äôre saving our beloved nation from the scourge of corruption and blind, wild growth of an increasingly oppressive federal government. It will not be easy, but our future depends upon our resolve.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share stories from across our district of individuals whose embody the spirit of service, leadership, and community. This week, I spoke on the House floor to honor the extraordinary life and legacy of a true Hometown Hero‚Äîthe late Jack Erickson of Newtown, whom we sadly lost at the end of March. 

Jack did not just live in our community‚Äîhe helped shape it. For 96 remarkable years, he led with strength, purpose, and a commitment to serving others. A proud @USArmy veteran, Eagle Scout, and nationally awarded photographer, including a first-place honor from the National Press Photo Association in 1951, Jack captured history through his lens, photographing icons like Marilyn Monroe and President Truman. But his greatest legacy wasn‚Äôt who he photographed‚Äîit was how he lifted those around him. 

Following his military service, Jack built a successful business career, serving as Eastern Regional Sales Manager for Staley Manufacturing Company and later as President of the Bucks County Board of REALTORS Sales Division. However, his commitment to public service is what made the deepest and most lasting impact. Jack spent more than three decades helping preserve the history of Upper Makefield as a longtime member of the Historical Architectural Review Board. He twice led the Washington Crossing Rotary Club, lived out the motto ‚ÄúService Above Self,‚Äù helped launch the local Kiwanis Club, and served as president of the Pennsbury Scholarship Foundation, opening doors of opportunity for generations of students. He was also a proud 40-year member of the Newtown Reliance Company‚Äîhelping keep local traditions alive. 

Jack was a leader, a mentor, and a loyal friend. Whether championing education, supporting local preservation, or simply showing up when it mattered most, embodying his values through action. Although he never sought attention, he earned the admiration and gratitude of an entire community. At age 90, he was named Newtown‚Äôs Aging Athlete of the Year, a testament to the energy and spirit that defined him. Even later in life, he greeted each day with joy and optimism. When asked how he was doing, he would flash a grin and say, ‚ÄúNear perfect.‚Äù 

We extend our deepest condolences to his family and the many friends and neighbors whose lives he touched. Jack showed us what it means to live a life of service, purpose, and joy. May we honor him not just with our words but by following his example‚Äîlifting others, showing up, and giving our best to the place we call home.

Name: Smith, Adam
text:
In this current moment, there is a crucial opportunity to bring partners together to blunt the influence of Iran and other extremist groups like ISIS and bring stability to the region. I recently led a congressional delegation to the Middle East and saw firsthand that we have partners who are ready and willing to work with us and with Israel to achieve this goal. However, Israel's current actions in Syria, Gaza, the West Bank and Lebanon run the risk of making these efforts at stability in the region much more difficult to achieve.

Israel is blocking the delivery of humanitarian aid into Gaza, enabling rapid settlement expansion and settler violence in the West Bank, and delegitimizing the new governments in Lebanon and Syria with military operations. I understand that Israel must defend itself against Hezbollah, Hamas and other Iranian proxies, but these extremist groups thrive in chaos and are able to recruit and gain support where populations in Gaza, the West Bank, Syria and Lebanon continue to suffer in active war zones. The only long-term hope is for stable governments to emerge in these places.

Israel must immediately allow humanitarian assistance back into Gaza. It should do far more to stop settler violence in the West Bank, and, crucially, it must work with Arab partners in the region to support Palestinian leadership that can be an alternative to Hamas and give all the Palestinian people some hope for the future. Additionally, Israel's continued attacks on and occupations of land in Lebanon and Syria threaten to undermine the fragile, fledgling efforts of each to build new peaceful and stable governments.

Bringing a coalition of partners together as a deterrence to Iran is the only way out of this cycle of regional conflict that has been devastating to the civilian population. Israel must immediately let humanitarian aid in, stop legitimizing settlements in the West Bank, and halt military actions that continue to contribute to the chaos in the region. Israel must change course or we risk losing this opportunity to achieve security and stability in the Middle East.

Name: Collins, Susan M.
text:
Today‚Äôs announcement from the University of Maine that it has received full funding for Maine Sea Grant is terrific news for the fishermen, lobstermen, hospitality workers, and so many others in Maine that rely on a productive and growing coastal economy.

After a February announcement from the Department of Commerce that the program was being defunded, I contacted Commerce Secretary Howard Lutnick and the Trump administration to explain all that is at stake for Maine‚Äôs coastal communities with the loss of Sea Grant funding. After several productive conversations, Secretary Lutnick directed NOAA to renegotiate the terms and conditions of the work to be performed by Maine Sea Grant to ensure that it focuses on advancing Maine‚Äôs coastal economies, working waterfronts, and sustainable fisheries, and, this week, they received their funding.

I am thrilled that Maine Sea Grant has received its full funding so that the important work they do to conduct research, support a robust pipeline of skilled labor, and enrich our state‚Äôs economy can continue unimpeded. Maine Sea Grant has more than 700 established partnerships with businesses, researchers, community organizations, and local and county governments, and their work contributed to $23.5 million in documented economic benefits in 2023 alone. For every $1 of funding for Maine Sea Grant, our state has seen a $15 return‚Äîthis is a valuable investment into Maine‚Äôs bright future.

Click here to read the announcement from the University of Maine: https://t.co/dcrLRPIXX5

This new mission not only secures Beale‚Äôs role in our national defense‚Äîit brings new technology, new capabilities, and new investment to our region. The future of the U.S. Air Force is being built right here at Beale.

Cudjo Banquante‚Äôs story is one of triumph in the face of hardship and injustice. He was brought to America against his will and sold into slavery, yet he fought for the new nation‚Äôs freedom and was eventually granted his own. Banquante‚Äôs contributions to American and New Jersey history are remarkable and his story deserves acclaim. Thank you to the NJ Historical Society, the Daughters of the American Revolution, and everyone who worked on this amazing project.

Name: Brownley, Julia
text:
President Trump‚Äôs budget doesn‚Äôt just make devastating cuts ‚Äì it cuts people out of the promise of America.

Justice Gorsuch lays out a serious problem: America is drowning in laws‚Äîtoo many rules, too many penalties‚Äîand they‚Äôre being enforced by unelected, unaccountable bureaucrats. These aren‚Äôt folks you voted for, and yet they‚Äôre deciding how you live.

¬∑ The U.S. Code (our body of law) is over 60,000 pages.
¬∑ The Federal Register (federal regulations) is 188,000 pages and counting.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
It didn‚Äôt used to be this way. The courts once served as a check on runaway legislation and executive overreach. Name: Menendez, Robert
text:
Last week, President Trump released his proposed 2026 federal budget - and it paints a troubling picture for so many Americans.

Let‚Äôs break down what it means for New Jersey. üßµ

Name: Menendez, Robert
text: First - and this is important - budgets are a reflection of the Administration‚Äôs values, and Trump‚Äôs budget not just fails to support American families, but it weakens the very institutions that support our democracy.

Name: Menendez, Robert
text:
Healthcare cuts put nearly 2 million New Jerseyans - pregnant women, children, seniors, and those with disabilities - at risk of losing access to care. 

That means fewer cancer screenings, less preventative care, more ER visits, and higher costs for everyone.

Name: Menendez, Robert
text:
Slashing affordable housing programs, specifically over $26 billion from federal rental assistance programs, and cutting the entire LIHEAP energy assistance program means more families without a safe, warm place to call home. 

We need to be investing in programs that make housing more affordable; this does the opposite.

Name: Menendez, Robert
text:
With education and childcare costs rising, the budget slashes $4.5 billion from K-12 education. That hurts working families the most - especially parents trying to stay in the workforce. 

These cuts weaken families and the economy.

Name: Menendez, Robert
text: For seniors, this budget cuts critical programs like the Commodity Supplemental Food Program. Cuts for seniors lead to impossible choices - between medicine and groceries and between staying warm and staying fed.

Name: Menendez, Robert
text:
Here‚Äôs the issue: How can families chase the American Dream when they‚Äôre worried about putting food on the table, losing their healthcare, or paying rent? 

It‚Äôs irresponsible to slash programs that hardworking people pay into while asking nothing of the wealthiest among us.

Name: Menendez, Robert
text:
And for our veterans, who‚Äôve sacrificed so much for this country, cutting VA healthcare, mental health services, and housing assistance is more than irresponsible; it‚Äôs a betrayal. 

Veterans put their lives on the line for us, and we must honor our commitment to them when they return home.

Name: Menendez, Robert

Spain‚Äôs nationwide blackouts should be a wake-up call for policymakers everywhere.

The question is simple: How do we prevent this kind of grid failure at home?

Here in the U.S., we have a clear path forward:

Name: Fedorchak, Julie
text:
.@TheFP is spot on: ‚ÄúIf these blackouts were caused by Spain‚Äôs green energy policies, as seems likely, these blackouts are a preview of the world to come.‚Äù
https://t.co/PyPAEyeHln

Name: Fedorchak, Julie
text:
Second, the U.S. must realign federal incentives with the types of energy sources we actually need.

By continuing to incentivize intermittent energy sources‚Äîlike wind and solar‚Äîthrough generous tax credits, we‚Äôre sending the absolute wrong signals to the market.

Name: Fedorchak, Julie
text:
First, we MUST stop shutting down reliable, dispatchable energy. This is not a political statement. It is a matter of physics.

Spain relied on wind and solar for 80% of its power, which is ultimately what jeopardized their grid.

Name: Fedorchak, Julie
text: @TheFP puts it this way: ‚ÄúAt¬†the time of the blackout, the country had a slim percentage of¬†dispatchable power generation¬†in the mix. For those new to power sector terminology,¬†dispatchable¬†means sources that can switch on to meet demand when you need them.‚Äù

Name: Fedorchak, Julie
text: That‚Äôs why I introduced the Ending Intermittent Energy Subsidies Act, common-sense legislation to responsibly phase out production & investment tax credits for wind and solar energy over the next five years.¬†The legislation restores market signals that prioritize grid security.

Name: Fedorchak, Julie
text: The bottomline: We must learn from Spain and recognize a secure grid requires power sources that are always available.

Name: Fedorchak, Julie
text:
Let‚Äôs champion an all-of-the-above energy approach that includes 24/7/365 nuclear, coal, and natural gas. 

We can‚Äôt be a beacon for the world‚Äîor even safe in our homes‚Äîif we are sitting in the dark without power.

Each of the 40+ committees, caucuses, and task forces I serve on stands for a real issue‚Äîand each week, I‚Äôm putting one in focus and the action we‚Äôre taking to solve it.

This week: the Bipartisan PFAS Task Force.

As Co-Chair and Founding Member, I‚Äôm leading a national, bipartisan effort to confront the PFAS crisis head-on‚Äîbecause no one should have to question whether their water, homes, or schools are safe.

Today, I officially relaunched the Task Force for the 119th Congress and welcomed new Co-Chairs: @RepDebDingell, @RepJenKiggans, & @repkmr. Together, we‚Äôre turning PFAS issues into action.

Here‚Äôs how we‚Äôre advancing this mission: ‚¨áÔ∏è

‚úîÔ∏è Driving bipartisan legislation like the PFAS-Free Procurement Act, which I just introduced last week to reduce harmful chemical exposure by prohibiting federal contracts for products containing PFOS and PFOA
‚úîÔ∏è Securing historic federal investments in PFAS research, remediation, and prevention
‚úîÔ∏è Educating Congress and the public on the severe health and environmental risks 
‚úîÔ∏è Holding polluters accountable and pushing for comprehensive cleanup
‚úîÔ∏è Protecting communities across the country, where families have lived in danger for far too long

PFAS is linked to cancer, liver damage, and developmental harm‚Äîand the science is clear: these chemicals have no place in our future.

text:

Today, a radical far-left activist, who was escorted out of my town hall last night by state police after repeatedly disrupting the event, disrespecting fellow attendees, abusing my staff, and ignoring orders by state police, compared her experience to the brutal murder of six million Jews in Nazi Germany. To be specific, she told a local reporter that the town hall felt like ‚ÄòGermany in 1938.‚Äô With all due respect, that‚Äôs insane and offensive. She needs help. Sadly, it is just another incendiary statement this individual has made over many years.

Folks, make no mistake, while many people attend these town halls to engage in discourse and honest debate, others do so with the sole objective of sowing chaos and attracting the attention of media more concerned with clickbait headlines, than they are with straight journalism.

The right to peaceably assemble and share one‚Äôs political views is the foundation of our democracy and a pillar of the First Amendment. It‚Äôs why I defied party leadership and decided to host public town halls this spring when most chose not to. I begrudge no one their opinion of me or my votes ‚Äì good or bad.  The only request made to attendees was that they follow some basic rules of decorum and treat fellow residents and my staff ‚Äì most of them young people who decided to pursue public service ‚Äì with respect and decency.  To the vast majority who did, thank you; to those who did not, shame on you.

Name: Hern, Kevin
text:
In Oklahoma, we know about energy.

Oklahoma is home to major players in the oil & gas industry - in fact, Tulsa was once the oil capital of the world. But did you know that Oklahoma is also one of the leading states in renewable energy as well?

That's because we understand that we need both. Solar and wind, so-called 'green' energy sources, are great. But we can't rely on them full-time. That's why we're always going to need nuclear power, natural gas, and coal. These traditional energy sources are reliable and provide Americans with accessible, affordable, dependable energy.

The recent power outages across Spain and Portugal prove this point. You don't need to go all-in on any one or the other. An all-of-the-above approach guarantees reliable energy access.

The whole world can learn a lesson from these blackouts: virtue signaling to the climate lobby will come at the expense of your power grid.

Today, on #NationalNursesDay, we honor the heroes in scrubs ‚Äì the ones who hold our hands in moments of fear, who work long shifts with little rest, and who show up for us every single day.

Nurses are the backbone of our healthcare system. They face challenges most of us can‚Äôt imagine, and still they lead with selflessness, compassion, resilience, and grace.

For me, this day is deeply personal. My mother, Mary, is a nurse. I watched her care for the sick with unwavering dedication and then come home to support a family with the same tireless love. My mother showed me what it means to serve others, to lead with compassion, and to never give up. Even after retiring from active practice, she spent years teaching the next generation of nurses.

To every nurse out there: thank you. Your strength inspires us and your care sustains us. You deserve not just our gratitude, but our unwavering support each and every day.

I serve on the Energy and Commerce Committee ‚Äî the committee in Congress that oversees Medicaid. Next week, we‚Äôll hold a ¬†markup to debate the Republican budget plan that would slash this vital program.

Every day until then, I‚Äôm sharing stories from LA County ‚Äî real people whose lives and care are at stake. If Republicans want to talk about cutting Medicaid, they need to face the human cost.
I‚Äôll be there to fight back. #ProtectMedicaid

(3/7) MYTH: The bill lacks basic consumer protections.

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text:
(2/7) MYTH: The bill does nothing to prevent stablecoins from being exploited by terrorists, cartels, and criminals.

FACT: The GENIUS Act requires all stablecoin issuers, even those based overseas, to be able to freeze and recover coins when ordered by U.S. authorities.

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text:

FACT: The GENIUS Act makes it clear that ethics laws apply to members of Congress and Senior Executives in the government.

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text:
(5/7) MYTH: The GENIUS Act doesn't impose guardrails on transactions between a stablecoin issuer & its affiliate.

FACT: The bill prevents companies from forcing people to buy other products/services just to use their coins, similar to anti-tying restrictions applicable to banks.

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text:

I look forward to welcoming Santiago, his devoted mother Stephanie Cardenas, and his supportive godmother Monica Alejandra Lopez to Washington, D.C. I am excited to show them around the U.S. Capitol for what I know will be a meaningful and memorable visit.

Thank you to Eduardo A. Garza Robles, CEO of UniTrade; Raul Reyes of the Stronger Together Foundation; Ray and Betsy Sanchez of Smiles from Heaven; and Laredo ISD for helping make this incredible experience possible. A heartfelt thank you as well to everyone who joined us today for the special send-off. Your presence made the moment even more meaningful and truly wonderful.

Santiago, we celebrate you. We hope this trip brings you joy, inspiration, and lots of smiles along the way.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
At today‚Äôs House Appropriations Homeland Security Subcommittee hearing, I was pleased to speak with @Sec_Noem about commonsense, bipartisan solutions to support the brave men and women working every day to keep our southern border secure.

We discussed the need for river roads so Border Patrol agents can access remote areas safely and efficiently. I also raised concerns about Carrizo cane, which blocks visibility and hampers patrol efforts along the river.

I highlighted the urgency of updating surveillance technology, streamlining the procurement process, and deploying more AST towers. Too many areas along the border still lack coverage, putting our agents at greater risk.

I also pressed for new investments in scanning technology at our ports of entry - where most contraband comes through - and shared concerns about potential cuts to @CBP pensions that would hurt our frontline personnel.

I was especially glad to hear Secretary Noem express her interest in visiting Laredo with me to see these challenges firsthand.

South Texas knows what works on the border. I‚Äôll keep fighting for smart, targeted investments that support our agents, protect our communities, and deliver results.

Name: Gottheimer, Josh
text:
First, I am demanding that the Trump Administration add more air traffic controllers to cover Newark Airport to immediately help reduce shortages ‚Äî and pay all the workers accordingly.

Our region ‚Äî where 20% of the nation‚Äôs GDP runs through ‚Äî is short about 40 air traffic controllers.

Name: Gottheimer, Josh
text:
Second, I am asking the FAA, working with the Port Authority, to conduct a review of the technical wiring and infrastructure for air traffic control ‚Äî especially the towers at Newark.

Last week, an old copper wire in an outdated tower wiped out all communications between controllers and planes for 90 seconds ‚Äî causing five air traffic controllers to go on trauma leave and worsening delays.

This is completely unacceptable. Tell me what you need, so we can get it to you.

Name: Gottheimer, Josh
text:
I have also called the CEO of United Airlines to ask him what he needs to get Newark‚Äôs airport moving at full capacity again.

I don‚Äôt want anyone going anywhere else. I want them to be able to go to EWR.

Name: Gottheimer, Josh
text: The bottom line is that this isn‚Äôt a partisan issue ‚Äî it's a matter of public safety. It‚Äôs about fixing a system that needs fixing.

Name: Gottheimer, Josh
text:
As for the delays, I am asking United to get better ahead of cancellations and flight changes, to give people more notice and complete flexibility on rebookings and refunds until this problem is solved.

I‚Äôve also asked the House Appropriations Committee to immediately put emergency resources into fixing both the technology and staffing issues.
